## ⭐ Interview Summary (2-Minute Answer)

> "To build a secure and high-performance Shopify application, I focus on both speed and security. For performance, I optimize images, use lazy loading, leverage Shopify's global CDN to serve static assets, reduce HTTP requests, and use GraphQL to fetch only the required data. For security, I ensure all communication uses HTTPS, authenticate merchants through Shopify's OAuth flow, securely store access tokens on the backend, verify webhook requests using HMAC signatures, and validate all user input before processing it. Together, these practices help create a Shopify application that is fast, secure, scalable, and provides a great experience for merchants and customers."

This gives you a single, end-to-end understanding of how performance and security fit together in a Shopify app, rather than treating them as unrelated concepts.

Can you Explain How You Handle Shopify API Integrations?
->"When integrating with Shopify APIs, I first authenticate the merchant using Shopify's OAuth flow. After the merchant grants the required permissions, Shopify provides an access token, which I securely store on the backend. Whenever my application needs data—such as products or orders—the frontend sends a request to my backend, and the backend uses the access token to call Shopify's Admin API, typically through GraphQL. I request only the fields I need to reduce payload size and improve performance. I also handle API errors gracefully, respect Shopify's rate limits, and use webhooks for event-driven updates instead of continuously polling the API. Before processing webhook requests, I verify their HMAC signatures to ensure they genuinely came from Shopify. This approach keeps the application secure, efficient, and aligned with Shopify's best practices."

How do you Approach Responsive Design on Shopify?
->"My approach to responsive design starts with a mobile-first mindset because many Shopify users shop on mobile devices. I build flexible layouts using Flexbox or CSS Grid, avoid fixed widths, and use media queries to adapt the layout for tablets and desktops. I optimize product images by requesting the correct image size from Shopify instead of loading full-resolution images, which improves both responsiveness and performance. For embedded Shopify apps, I use Polaris components because they are responsive and follow Shopify's design system. Finally, I test the application on multiple screen sizes and browsers to ensure the navigation, product cards, forms, and buttons provide a consistent and user-friendly experience across all devices."

How can you Customise the Checkout Process in Shopify?
->"My approach to checkout customization depends on Shopify's supported extension points. I don't modify Shopify's core checkout because it contains sensitive payment and customer information. Instead, I use Checkout UI Extensions to add custom user interface elements such as gift wrap options, delivery instructions, or loyalty messages. For backend business logic like discounts, shipping rules, or payment method customization, I use Shopify Functions. I also ensure that any customizations follow Shopify's security model, work over HTTPS, and integrate cleanly with the rest of the app through APIs and webhooks. This approach keeps the checkout secure, maintainable, and aligned with Shopify's best practices."

How can you add a new Product to a Shopify Store?
->"To add a new product to a Shopify store, I first ensure the merchant has installed my app through Shopify's OAuth flow. This gives my backend a secure access token. When the merchant fills out the product form in the frontend, the data is sent to my backend, where I validate the input. The backend then uses the stored access token to call Shopify's Admin GraphQL API with a productCreate mutation. Shopify verifies the token, creates the product, and returns the new product details. My backend sends the response back to the frontend, which displays a success message. If needed, Shopify can also send a product/create webhook, which I verify using HMAC before processing."

A Shopify Theme and a Shopify App serve different purposes. A Theme controls the storefront's appearance, including the layout, colors, fonts, product pages, and overall user interface. Themes are primarily built using HTML, CSS, JavaScript, and Shopify's Liquid templating language.

A Shopify App, on the other hand, extends the store's functionality. Apps can add features such as product reviews, loyalty programs, inventory management, discounts, or integrations with external services. Shopify apps are commonly built with technologies like React, Remix, Node.js, GraphQL, and the Shopify Admin API.

Can you Explain the Difference Between a Shopify Theme and a Shopify App?
->A good way to think about it is that the Theme is responsible for how the store looks, while the App is responsible for what the store can do. In many real-world stores, both work together—for example, a review app manages review data, and the theme displays those reviews on the product page."


